\strong{Note:} This answer is based on a similar question that I answered on The Workplace. The question was: [What can I do to show other women (currently employed in tech) that it’s worth it to speak up about sexism when it happens?](https://workplace.stackexchange.com/q/18218/14993)

\section{Answer:}

\begin{blockquote}

I've been thinking a lot about how to make an argument about this issue to other women in tech (or other male-dominated fields). I think it can be hard to speak up when you see sexism happen, and I think that sometimes people think that if they just ignore it, it will go away, or that the person "doesn't mean it" or "is just joking around".
\end{blockquote}

\em{Just because a company is a “tech company” does not mean that the company doesn’t have an obligation to employees to ensure that they are working in a safe, healthy environment.}

\section{Reasons to Speak Up}

\strong{1. Your coworkers are not your friends.}

\em{We know that we are not going to be friends with every person we work with. However, we are still accountable to one another when we are at work. We are required to follow our company policies. If someone is not following those policies, we need to report it.}

\strong{2. It’s not personal.}

\em{It’s too easy to see “sexism” as a personal attack against you. It’s not. It’s a systematic issue that is pervasive throughout our society. This is not to say that it is not harmful or that it doesn’t personally affect you. But it is not a personal attack.}

\strong{3. It’s not about you.}

\em{Often, the people that we work with are not the people that are causing the problem. It is not about you. It is about the system that allows the problem to exist. By speaking up, you are taking action to change the system.}

\strong{4. You are not alone.}

\em{It is easy to feel that you are the only one that has this problem. You are not. It is a systemic problem that has existed for a long time. We are in this together. By speaking up, you are standing in solidarity with those who have suffered from sexism in the past, and with those who will suffer from it in the future.}

\strong{5. It’s not your fault.}

\em{This is important. You did not cause this problem. No one can force you to tolerate this kind of behavior. If you are being treated unfairly, you are entitled to report it. You are not responsible for other people’s behavior.}

\strong{6. It’s not just about you.}

\em{This is about other women who may be experiencing the same thing. If you stay silent, you are enabling this behavior to remain. By speaking up, you are speaking out for those other women and for the future of all women in your company.}

\strong{7. It’s not about you feeling “safe.”}

\em{This is about the system of power that is in place. We are not discussing whether you feel safe. We are discussing whether it is safe to work in that environment. If you are being treated unfairly, it is not safe. If you are being treated unfairly, you should speak up.}

\strong{8. You are not responsible for other people’s feelings.}

\em{If someone is offended by your speaking up, that is not your problem. If someone is offended by your speaking up, that is their problem. You are not responsible for their feelings.}

\strong{9. You are not responsible for other people’s behavior.}

\em{If someone is offended by your speaking up, it is not your responsibility to make sure that they are not offended. If someone is offended by your speaking up, that is their problem. You are not responsible for their behavior.}

\strong{10. You are not responsible for other people’s reactions.}

