This is a very common misunderstanding of dependency injection.  It's not a black and white distinction between DI and non-DI.  The important part is not whether you use the `new` keyword or not, it's how you get your dependencies.

The essence of DI, in my opinion, is that you shouldn't do `new`ing when you need a dependency.  That's it.  That's the rule.  So if you're using `new` then you're not doing DI.  But that doesn't mean you have to use 3rd party DI frameworks to do DI.

For example, let's say you have a controller that uses a dependency.  This is the non-DI way:

\begin{code}
class MyController
{
    public MyController()
    {
        this.myDependency = new MyDependency();
    }

    public MyDependency myDependency { get; private set; }

    public void DoSomething()
    {
        this.myDependency.DoSomething();
    }
}
\end{code}

Now, let's say you're using a DI framework.  Instead of using `new`, you inject your dependency through the DI framework.  This is the DI way:

\begin{code}
class MyController
{
    public MyController(MyDependency myDependency)
    {
        this.myDependency = myDependency;
    }

    public MyDependency myDependency { get; private set; }

    public void DoSomething()
    {
        this.myDependency.DoSomething();
    }
}
\end{code}

Now, let's say you're not using a DI framework, but you really want to do DI.  There are a few ways you can do this.  One way is to make your controller a factory for the dependency:

\begin{code}
class MyController
{
    public MyController(MyDependency myDependency)
    {
        this.myDependency = myDependency;
    }

    public MyDependency myDependency { get; private set; }

    public void DoSomething()
    {
        this.myDependency.DoSomething();
    }

    public IMyDependency GetMyDependency()
    {
        return new MyDependency();
    }

}
\end{code}

Another way is to use a singleton:

\begin{code}
class MyController
{
    private static IMyDependency _myDependency;

    public MyController()
    {
    }

    public MyDependency myDependency
    {
        get
        {
            return _myDependency;
        }
    }

    public void DoSomething()
    {
        this.myDependency.DoSomething();
    }

    public static IMyDependency GetMyDependency()
    {
        if (_myDependency == null)
        {
            _myDependency = new MyDependency();
        }

        return _myDependency;
    }
}
\end{code}

Now, the DI framework way is not necessarily the best way.  But it's just one way of doing DI.  It's not the only way.  DI is about not using `new`, not about using `new` or about using 3rd party frameworks.

So I would say that the important thing is to use the dependency wherever you need it, \strong{and} to not use `new` when you get it.  You can do the latter without the former.  You can do the former without the latter.  But you can't do the former \em{without} the latter.

