\strong{Dependency Injection} is a technique in which a dependency (like a class, or a method) is passed to a class/method by an external source.

It is mostly used with IoC containers, but it can also be done manually.

The main idea is that instead of a class instantiating its dependencies, they are brought to it.

\begin{code}
public class ClassA
{
    private readonly ClassB _b;

    public ClassA(ClassB b)
    {
        _b = b;
    }

    public void DoSomething()
    {
        // ...
    }
}

public class ClassB
{
    public void DoSomething()
    {
        // ...
    }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var b = new ClassB();
        var a = new ClassA(b);
        a.DoSomething();
    }
}
\end{code}

As you can see, in this example, `ClassA` instantiates `ClassB`.

This can be a problem when `ClassB` is complex or has a lot of dependencies.

This can get messy because `ClassA` needs to know about `ClassB`:

\begin{code}
public class ClassA
{
    private readonly ClassB _b;

    public ClassA(ClassB b)
    {
        _b = b;
    }

    public void DoSomething()
    {
        _b.DoSomething();
    }
}

public class ClassB
{
    private readonly ClassC _c;

    public ClassB(ClassC c)
    {
        _c = c;
    }

    public void DoSomething()
    {
        _c.DoSomething();
    }
}

public class ClassC
{
    public void DoSomething()
    {
        // ...
    }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var b = new ClassB(new ClassC());
        var a = new ClassA(b);
        a.DoSomething();
    }
}
\end{code}

With this example, `ClassA` still needs to know about `ClassB` (because it needs to call `DoSomething()`) and `ClassB` needs to know about `ClassC`.

This can get messy, and sometimes you might not even know that a class has some dependencies, and you might miss them.

This can be solved by dependency injection.

Instead of creating the objects and passing them to the method, we can inject those objects instead.

\begin{code}
public class ClassA
{
    private readonly ClassB _b;

    public ClassA(ClassB b)
    {
        _b = b;
    }

    public void DoSomething()
    {
        _b.DoSomething();
    }
}

public class ClassB
{
    private readonly ClassC _c;

    public ClassB(ClassC c)
    {
        _c = c;
    }

    public void DoSomething()
    {
        _c.DoSomething();
    }
}

public class ClassC
{
    public void DoSomething()
    {
        // ...
    }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var a = new ClassA(new ClassB(new ClassC()));
        a.DoSomething();
    }
}
\end{code}

Instead of creating the objects, we just pass the dependencies to `ClassA`.

Answer: Dependency injection is a technique in which a dependency is injected into a class.

The dependency may be required for the class to function correctly, or may be required for the class to function correctly under certain circumstances.

Dependency injection is usually used to pass in a dependency that is not known at design time.

The paper is quite old, and their "Lottery Ticket Hypothesis" was later extended to the more general [Tailored Architecture Search](https://arxiv.org/abs/1706.02207) (TAS) model. I'll give a summary of both.

\section{The Lottery Ticket Hypothesis}

The paper begins by asking, "What is the expected performance of the first layer of a randomly initialized deep neural network?". Intuitively, we expect this to be very poor because the weights are initialized randomly. However, the paper shows that this is false.

\begin{blockquote}

In fact, we find that the output of a single randomly initialized layer is often quite predictive, and can be nearly as accurate as a trained layer. This paradoxical phenomenon is known as the lottery ticket hypothesis.
\end{blockquote}

This is because the weights of a random neural network tend to fall into a number of regions of low loss, which are often connected. If you train the network from scratch, it is quite likely that the weights will randomly end up in one of these "low loss" regions and will have a low error.

These regions of low loss are called "winning tickets" or "winning weights" in the paper. The authors propose a new algorithm, called "lottery ticket training", which aims to find these "winning weights".

\section{Tailored Architecture Search}

TAS, unlike LTH, searches for a complete neural network rather than a single layer. It works by first randomly initializing a neural network. Then, the weights are optimized to minimize the loss on the training data. However, the network is then "frozen". This means that the weights are fixed and no further training is performed.

The next step is to apply a number of different "modifications" to the network. These modifications can be things like adding/removing layers, changing the size of the layers, or changing the activation functions. The goal is to find a set of modifications that result in a network with low loss.

\begin{blockquote}

Our modifications are inspired by a simple yet profound observation: the most successful modifications to a random network tend to be those that remove weights from the network, rather than those that add weights.
\end{blockquote}

The authors show that this "pruning" technique can be used to find networks with low loss, and that these networks are often simpler than the original network.

I hope this gives you a good idea of what the paper is about.

