It depends on the company and on the position you would be offered. For instance, the same company might offer you a higher salary if you are an entry-level Software Engineer than if you were an experienced one.

\section{How to find out}

The best way to find out the average salary for a certain job is to check [Glassdoor](https://www.glassdoor.com). For the US it should be reliable and accurate.

\section{How to approach the question}

The best way to approach this question is to make a good impression during the technical interview. Once you receive an offer and you are asked for your salary expectations, you can state that you would be interested in [x]. The company will likely offer you a bit higher than that.

The key is to have a number in your head. However, don't make it too high so that you are not taken seriously. For instance, if you are a recent graduate and you can get an offer from a FAANG company, then you should expect a higher salary (in the ~$130k per year) than someone who has been working for 5 years and is only looking for a position at a FAANG company.

I have found a solution to this problem, and it is as follows:
\begin{itemize}
\item Embed the positions of the word tokens into a matrix of the form:
\end{itemize}

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
\overbrace{pos_1}^{\text{word token 1}} & \overbrace{pos_2}^{\text{word token 2}} & \overbrace{pos_3}^{\text{word token 3}} & \ldots & \overbrace{pos_{n_1}}^{\text{word token n_1}} \\
\end{bmatrix}
$$

We can do this by running the sentences through a [`SentencePiece`](https://github.com/google/sentencepiece) encoder, which will return a tensor of the form:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
\overbrace{pos_1}^{\text{word token 1}} & \overbrace{pos_2}^{\text{word token 2}} & \overbrace{pos_3}^{\text{word token 3}} & \ldots & \overbrace{pos_{n_1}}^{\text{word token n_1}} \\
\end{bmatrix}
$$

This tensor will contain a list of indices for each word token in the sentence.

Now, to embed this information into a position matrix:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
\overbrace{pos_1}^{\text{word token 1}} & \overbrace{pos_2}^{\text{word token 2}} & \overbrace{pos_3}^{\text{word token 3}} & \ldots & \overbrace{pos_{n_1}}^{\text{word token n_1}} \\
\end{bmatrix}
$$

We can simply create a 2-dimensional position matrix, with the positions of each word token as the dimensions of the matrix.
\begin{itemize}
\item Embed the words of the sentence into vectors
\item Create a matrix with the words of the sentence as rows and the position matrix as columns
\item Multiply the two matrices together to get the original sentence's embeddings
\end{itemize}

