Answer: I'll attempt to answer your questions in the order you've presented them.

\begin{blockquote}

How did it happen? Was it a single event or a series of events?
\end{blockquote}

It is generally assumed that there was a singularity at the beginning of time. However, the exact nature of this singularity is not known, and there are a few different ideas regarding it. Some of the ideas are:
\begin{itemize}
\item The universe may have been "created" from a singularity.
\item There may have been a "quantum fluctuation" in which the universe appeared from nothing.
\item A "meta-universe" was created, and our universe is just one of many.
\end{itemize}

\begin{blockquote}

What was the universe before this happened?
\end{blockquote}

This is an interesting question, and I don't think anyone knows for sure. There are a few different theories, but I'll just list one. The idea is that the universe was created "from nothing". That is, the quantum fluctuation I mentioned before occurred. The energy density of the fluctuation could be either positive or negative. In the positive case, you have a singularity which expands and becomes our universe. But what if it was negative? In that case, we would have the Big Bang, but we would never have seen it. A lot of people don't like this idea, as it sort of violates the second law of thermodynamics.

\begin{blockquote}

What were the laws of physics before this happened?
\end{blockquote}

To my knowledge, we don't know what the laws of physics were before the Big Bang.

\begin{blockquote}

What was the composition of the universe before this happened?
\end{blockquote}

We don't know what the composition of the universe was before the Big Bang.

\begin{blockquote}

What is the composition of the universe like now?
\end{blockquote}

The composition of the universe is mostly what we call "dark energy".

\begin{blockquote}

How do we know the Big Bang happened?
\end{blockquote}

The Big Bang is the best theory to describe the current state of the universe. There are some other theories that describe the current state of the universe well, but they don't explain how we got here in the first place. Plus, the Big Bang theory is the most consistent with observations.

\begin{blockquote}

How do we know what happened at the Big Bang?
\end{blockquote}

We don't know exactly what happened at the Big Bang. However, we can make some predictions based on the Big Bang theory. For example, we can predict what the composition of the universe was when it was very young.

