There are three broad approaches to describing an action in football:
\begin{itemize}
\item a narrative approach, which makes the action flow
\item a play-by-play approach, which goes through the action step by step
\item a description approach, which describes the action in more general terms
\end{itemize}

I'll give an example of each.

\strong{1. A narrative approach}

\begin{blockquote}

The team was behind by 14 points with only 30 seconds left. They had a chance at a comeback if the quarterback could connect with the receiver on a deep pass. The ball was snapped and the quarterback dropped back to pass. He looked downfield and spotted the receiver 20 yards away. He started to throw but the receiver was covered and the pass was broken up by the opposing cornerback. The quarterback looked left and right but he didn't see any open receivers. The clock was ticking down and he was running out of time. The line broke down and the quarterback was sacked. The quarterback was in great fear of getting injured but he had to stay in the play. He got up and ran to the sideline.
\end{blockquote}

This is a narrative approach which describes the action in great detail. The reader is taken through the play from start to finish. Here are some examples of words that were used to describe the action in this approach:
\begin{itemize}
\item \em{The team was behind by 14 points with only 30 seconds left.}
\item \em{he had a chance at a comeback if the quarterback could connect with the receiver on a deep pass}
\item \em{The ball was snapped and the quarterback dropped back to pass}
\item \em{He looked downfield and spotted the receiver 20 yards away}
\item \em{He started to throw but the receiver was covered and the pass was broken up by the opposing cornerback}
\item \em{The quarterback looked left and right but he didn't see any open receivers}
\item \em{The clock was ticking down and he was running out of time}
\item \em{The line broke down and the quarterback was sacked}
\item \em{the quarterback was in great fear of getting injured}
\end{itemize}

\strong{2. A play-by-play approach}

\begin{blockquote}

The quarterback took the snap and started to throw. The pass was broken up by the cornerback. The quarterback had no other options left and was sacked.
\end{blockquote}

This is a play-by-play approach which gives a step-by-step account of the action. The reader learns what happened, but doesn't get any extra information about the action. Here are some examples of words that were used:
\begin{itemize}
\item \em{The quarterback took the snap}
\item \em{he started to throw}
\item \em{the quarterback had no other options left}
\item \em{he was sacked}
\end{itemize}

\strong{3. A description approach}

\begin{blockquote}

The quarterback took the snap and with a quick release he threw the ball 20 yards downfield. The receiver was covered, but the pass was broken up by the cornerback. The quarterback had no other options left and was sacked.
\end{blockquote}

This is a description approach which uses a combination of verbs to explain what happened. The reader is given a "big picture" of the action, but the reader doesn't get a detailed account. Here are some examples of words that were used:
\begin{itemize}
\item \em{The quarterback took the snap and with a quick release he threw the ball 20 yards downfield}
\item \em{the quarterback had no other options left}
\end{itemize}

\begin{blockquote}

In my opinion, the best approach for describing an action is a narrative approach.
\end{blockquote}

