The problem is that you are not using the `copy()` function. You are using the `append()` function which modifies the list.

\begin{code}
   my_list = [1,2,3,4]
   new_list = []
   for x in my_list:
       new_list.append(x)
\end{code}

This will actually modify the list and when you check for `id`s, you will see that `new_list` and `my_list` have the same id.

You need to use the `copy()` function to actually get a list that will be independent of the original.

\begin{code}
import copy
   my_list = [1,2,3,4]
   new_list = copy.copy(my_list)
   for x in my_list:
       new_list.append(x)
\end{code}

This will create a list which will be independent of the original.

