\strong{I) Average speed is not affected by the number of laps}

\begin{blockquote}

Jeff takes 20 minutes to jog around the race course one time, and 25
  minutes to jog around a second time.
\end{blockquote}

In this sentence, the first time and the second time are two different things. The first time is the time it takes Jeff to jog around the race course one time. The second time is the time it takes Jeff to jog around a second time.

\begin{blockquote}

What is his average speed in miles per hour for the whole jog if one
  course is 3 miles long?
\end{blockquote}

This is the average speed during the whole jog, which is the average speed when Jeff jogged around the race course one time and when he jogged around a second time.

\strong{II) Average speed is not affected by the distance}

\begin{blockquote}

If one course is 3 miles long
\end{blockquote}

This affects the distance, but it does not affect the average speed. The average speed is calculated by the average velocity (which is calculated by the distance and the time) over one period. The distance is calculated by the length of the race course and the number of laps. The time is calculated by the time it takes to jog around the race course one time and the time it takes to jog around a second time.

\strong{III) Average speed is affected by the time}

\begin{blockquote}

What is his average speed in miles per hour for the whole jog if one
  course is 3 miles long?
\end{blockquote}

This is the average speed during the whole jog. The average speed is calculated by the average velocity over a period. The average velocity is calculated by the distance and the time.

\strong{IV) Average speed is affected by the distance and the time}

\begin{blockquote}

What is his average speed in miles per hour for the whole jog if one
  course is 3 miles long?

The average speed is calculated by the average velocity over one period.

The average velocity is calculated by the distance and the time.

The distance is calculated by the length of the race course and the number of laps.

The time is calculated by the time it takes to jog around the race course one time and the time it takes to jog around a second time.
\end{blockquote}

\strong{The correct answer}

We can formulate the problem as follows:

\begin{blockquote}

Jeff takes 20 minutes to jog around the race course one time, and 25
  minutes to jog around a second time. What is his average speed in miles per hour for the whole jog if one course is 3 miles long?
\end{blockquote}

\begin{itemize}
\item The distance is calculated by the length of the race course and the number of laps.
\item The time is calculated by the time it takes to jog around the race course one time and the time it takes to jog around a second time.
\item The average velocity is calculated by the distance and the time.
\item The average speed is calculated by the average velocity over one period.
\end{itemize}

