\begin{blockquote}

[A] NEW artificial intelligence robot that can assist people in brainstorming and literary creation.
\end{blockquote}

This is wordy and awkward.  I'd suggest a more simple and direct approach:

\begin{blockquote}

NEW artificial intelligence robot to assist people in brainstorming
  and literary creation.
\end{blockquote}

\begin{blockquote}

Please write an advertisement for it.
\end{blockquote}

An advertisement is a way of informing the public of a product or service, with the expectation that the public will purchase/use this product or service.  It is not used for other forms of announcement, for example, an announcement that a new artificial intelligence robot has been developed.

If you want an advertisement for this new artificial intelligence robot, you need a way to measure response.  In which case, you need to have a product or service to sell.  For example, a web site where users can pay to use the robot.  Or perhaps the robot itself, which will be sold to the public.

If you want to advertise that the robot has been developed, then you just need an announcement.  For example:

\begin{blockquote}

Announcement: We have developed a new artificial intelligence robot that can assist people in brainstorming and literary creation.
\end{blockquote}

\begin{blockquote}

I have developed a robot that can assist people in brainstorming and literary creation.
\end{blockquote}

This is a better way to phrase this.  For one thing, it is less wordy.  For another, it is a straightforward factual statement.  It is not an advertisement, which is a way of promoting a product or service that is not yet available.

