The other answers are good, but I would like to point out that the [standard](https://www.ecma-international.org/publications-and-standards/standards/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-ecmascript-language-lexical-environment) for JavaScript does not actually require `eval` to fail on that particular case. In the case where the code is `eval("foo")` instead of `eval("eval('foo')`) then the code will be parsed.

\begin{code}
var code = 'eval("foo")';
var result = eval(code);
\end{code}

Then the `eval` will return `undefined`, but it will still parse the code.

It is not required by the standard, but it is still a good idea to prevent this code. It is possible to parse code that is not valid JavaScript and would not be valid in a normal situation.

Comment: This is useful. Thanks!

Comment: This is a very important point.  It's not just about the code that can be parsed, but also code that can be parsed and executed.  `eval("eval('foo')")` is not valid JavaScript, so it can't be executed, but `eval('eval("foo")')` will execute.

