Answer: \begin{code}
find ~/data -type f -exec ls -ltr {} +
\end{code}

The `-exec` option of the `find` command specifies that it will execute `ls` on each file it finds.  The `{}` is a placeholder for the file name, so it would be replaced by the name of the file found.

The `+` is just a way to say that it will execute `ls` on more than one file at a time.  This is important, because `ls` is slow.

This command will list the files in the subdirectories of `~/data` and will show the date and time when the file was last modified.

