\strong{Theorem.} If $S$ is a countably infinite set, then $\exists A\subseteq S\text{ such that }A$ is uncountable.
\end{blockquote}

\strong{Proof.}

\begin{blockquote}

Let $S$ be a countably infinite set, and $A=S$. Then $A$ is uncountable, as it is the same size as $S$, which is countably infinite.
\end{blockquote}

\strong{Claim:} In particular, if $A$ is a set of real numbers, then there is an uncountable real number.

\strong{Proof.}

\begin{blockquote}

Suppose $A=\{1,2,\ldots,n\}$. Choose $a\in A$ and let $A'=A\setminus \{a\}$. Then $A'$ has the same number of real numbers as $A$, so it is uncountable. We can do this for every real number $a$, so there are uncountably many real numbers.
\end{blockquote}

\strong{Claim:} In particular, there is an uncountable set of real numbers that are not countable.

\strong{Proof.}

\begin{blockquote}

Suppose $\{a_1,a_2,\ldots,a_n\}$ is a countable set of real numbers. Choose $a\in S\setminus \{a_1,a_2,\ldots,a_n\}$. Let $A=\{a_1,a_2,\ldots,a_n\}\cup \{a\}$. Then $A$ has the same number of real numbers as $S$, so it is uncountable. We can do this for every real number $a$, so there are uncountably many real numbers that are not in a countable set.
\end{blockquote}

\strong{Claim:} In particular, there is an uncountable set of real numbers, whose elements are not countable.

\strong{Proof.}

\begin{blockquote}

Suppose $\{a_1,a_2,\ldots,a_n\}$ is a countable set of real numbers. Choose $a\in S\setminus \{a_1,a_2,\ldots,a_n\}$. Let $A=\{a_1,a_2,\ldots,a_n\}\cup \{a\}$. Then $A$ has the same number of real numbers as $S$, so it is uncountable. We can do this for every real number $a$, so there are uncountably many real numbers that are not countable.
\end{blockquote}

