\begin{blockquote}

Why is the musical scale the way it is: 12 keys: 7 major, 5 minor?
\end{blockquote}

This is a rather broad question, so let me try to address it in a general way.

\section{The "music of the world"}

First of all, \strong{there is no single "musical scale"}. There are hundreds of different scales, with different numbers of notes, different intervals between the notes, etc. There are scales that are used in different countries around the world, and there are scales that are specific to certain cultures or communities. There are scales used in Western music, and scales that are used in Eastern and other types of music.

And there are scales that are used in different types of music. For example, there are scales that are used in classical music, scales that are used in jazz, scales that are used in rock, and so on.

\section{The "Western" scales}

Some of the scales that are used in Western music are:
\begin{itemize}
\item The [chromatic scale](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromatic_scale), which has 12 semitones (half-steps), and is often used in jazz and rock music.
\item The [major scale](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_scale), which has 7 whole steps (whole notes) and 1 half step. This scale is often used in classical music, and in many Western popular styles.
\item The [minor scale](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minor_scale), which has 7 whole steps and 1 half step. This scale is used in classical music, and in many Western popular styles.
\item The [blues scale](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blues_scale), which has 6 whole steps and 1 half step. This scale is used in jazz, blues, rock, and many other styles.
\item The [pentatonic scale](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentatonic_scale), which has 5 whole steps and 2 half steps. This scale is used in many traditional styles, particularly in Eastern Asian and African music.
\end{itemize}

These are just a few examples of the many different scales that are used in Western music.

\section{Why are there so many different scales?}

The answer to this question is not really simple. Different scales have been used for different reasons. For example, some scales are used because they are easier to play on certain instruments, while others are used because they sound good together.

Some scales are used because they are associated with certain emotions or moods. For example, the major scale is often used to convey happiness, while the minor scale is often used to convey sadness.

Some scales are used because they are associated with certain cultural traditions. For example, the pentatonic scale is often used in traditional Chinese music, while the blues scale is often used in traditional African American music.

In short, there are many different scales because they have been used for many different reasons.

\section{Why is the major scale so important?}

The major scale is important because it is the basis for many other scales. For example, the minor scale is just the major scale with one note lowered.

The major scale is also the basis for many chords. For example, the C major chord is just a C major scale played together.

The major scale is also the basis for many melodies. For example, the "Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star" melody is just a C major scale played in a certain order.

In short, the major scale is important because it is the basis for many other scales, chords, and melodies.

\section{Why are there 12 notes in an octave?}

There are 12 notes in an octave because that is the way the human ear perceives sound. The human ear can perceive frequencies from 20 Hz (cycles per second) to 20,000 Hz. Above 20,000 Hz, the sound is too high for the human ear to perceive.

The human ear can also perceive intervals, or the difference between two notes. The smallest interval that the human ear can perceive is the semitone, which is a half step.

