Wikipedia's [History of kissing](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kiss) has some information on the subject.

\begin{blockquote}

A kiss is a touch or press of one's lips against another person or an object. Cultural connotations of kissing vary widely. In some countries, kissing is the usual greeting between even casual acquaintances. In other cultures, kissing is a familiar greeting between family members and close friends. As a romantic gesture, kissing may be used as a greeting, to express affection, good luck, romance or sympathy. In some countries, kissing is a standard part of farewell, especially if the encounter was brief.
\end{blockquote}

The first mention of kissing as a symbol of affection seems to go back to the 17th century.

\begin{blockquote}

Early modern Europe

\begin{blockquote}

During the early modern period, kissing began to be described as an expression of romantic love. A 1623 English book describes a "kiss of love", "a kiss of delight", and a "kiss of good-bye". The 1641 play The Spanish Curate by Nicolas Antonio describes a kiss as "the greatest pledge of love."

  </blockquote>
\end{blockquote}

\strong{The Romans invented the kiss as a sign of affection.}

The Romans kissed each other on the cheek, or on the lips in intimate situations.  The Romans also greeted each other by kissing the hand of the person they were greeting.  In fact, the Roman greeting "Salve" (Hello) was actually a kissing gesture.

The Romans spread this practice across Europe, and even the English adopted the practice of kissing on the cheek (with the right cheek being presented to the other person).  The French, on the other hand, kissed each other on the lips.

\begin{blockquote}

We don’t know when the Romans first kissed each other as a greeting, but we do know that by the time of the poet Virgil (70–19 BC), it was a commonplace. (“You kissed your mother, kiss me too, my dearest boy,” says the mother’s friend in the fourth eclogue.) Romans kissed each other on both cheeks, and the kiss was accompanied by a ritual of hand-shaking, followed by a ceremonial embrace.

  _{[kissing.org](http://www.kissing.org/history-of-kissing/)}
\end{blockquote}

Answer: The Roman Empire was one of the most influential civilizations in history. Roman culture was spread across Europe and the Mediterranean, eventually influencing the Byzantine Empire, and later on, European civilization. The Romans, like many other European cultures, greeted each other with a kiss. The kiss was a sign of respect and affection. This kissing greeting spread to many cultures around the world.

