I've found that the most efficient way to get the message across that documentation is important has been to use metrics.

A good way to get started is to do the following:

\section{1. Analyze the pain}

First, you need to figure out what the current pain is.  In my case, I found that most developers had a good idea of how documentation should be done, but were either too lazy or felt that their task was more important than documentation.  After a while, the documentation was either out of date, or simply never existed.

\section{2. Identify the stakeholders}

Next, you need to find out who the stakeholders are.  In my case, the stakeholders were the following:
\begin{itemize}
\item Developers
\item Product Managers
\item Product Owners
\item Sales
\item Executives
\item Support
\end{itemize}

\section{3. Identify the metrics}

So now you need to figure out what would be the best metrics to use to measure your progress.  In my case, I used the following:
\begin{itemize}
\item Number of bugs reported by developers
\item Number of bugs reported by support staff
\item Average time to reproduce bugs
\item Customer Satisfaction Score
\item Customer Churn Rate
\end{itemize}

\section{4. Analyze the metrics}

Once you have the metrics, you need to analyze them.  In my case, I found that the following metrics were the most important:
\begin{itemize}
\item Number of bugs reported by developers
\item Number of bugs reported by support staff
\item Average time to reproduce bugs
\item Customer Satisfaction Score
\end{itemize}

\section{5. Meet with the stakeholders}

Now that you have the metrics, you need to meet with the stakeholders and explain what you found.  In my case, I met with the following people:
\begin{itemize}
\item Developers
\item Product Managers
\item Product Owners
\item Sales
\item Executives
\item Support
\end{itemize}

\section{6. Get buy-in}

Now that you have the buy-in, it's time to implement your plan.  In my case, I implemented the following changes:
\begin{itemize}
\item Every developer was required to write at least one article per week
\item Every developer was required to write at least one article per month
\item Every developer was required to update their article at least once per month
\end{itemize}

\section{7. Measure the results}

Now that you have implemented your plan, it's time to measure the results.  In my case, I measured the following results:
\begin{itemize}
\item Number of bugs reported by developers
\item Number of bugs reported by support staff
\item Average time to reproduce bugs
\item Customer Satisfaction Score
\end{itemize}

\section{8. Iterate}

Now that you have measured the results, it's time to iterate.  In my case, I iterated the following changes:
\begin{itemize}
\item Every developer was required to write at least one article per week
\item Every developer was required to write at least one article per month
\item Every developer was required to update their article at least once per month
\end{itemize}

\section{9. Repeat}

Now that you have iterated the changes, it's time to repeat the process.  In my case, I repeated the process until the metrics were at a satisfactory level.

Comment: For bonus points, consider measuring the number of articles per developer, number of articles per week, or number of articles per month.

