\begin{blockquote}

In my opinion, the best way to judge a PhD candidate is by talking to them.
\end{blockquote}

I agree with this.  A PhD candidate should be able to discuss their work in a way that is not only comprehensible to their advisor, but also to other people in the field.  The key is that the candidate is able to take an abstract, complex idea and explain it in a way that has meaning for the listener.  That's no easy task.

\begin{blockquote}

I'm not a professor, but I am a PhD candidate in my second year in a top 50 program.
\end{blockquote}

It's fine if you're not a professor.  There are many other ways to judge a candidate.

\begin{blockquote}

As a PhD candidate, I have met many candidates from other programs.
\end{blockquote}

Good.  This is an excellent way to get a feel for what's out there.  But, again, your opinion is not a substitute for your advisor's.

\begin{blockquote}

I'm looking for specific indicators (not the obvious ones like GPA) that would distinguish a candidate in my program from the rest of the pack.
\end{blockquote}

I would say that GPA is a very good indicator.  A GPA of 3.8 or higher is often considered to be excellent for a PhD candidate.  A GPA of 3.5 or higher is usually excellent.  This is, of course, just one indicator.  It's also possible for a GPA to be misleading.  For example, an undergraduate who got all A's may not be a good PhD candidate if they were in an easy program.  On the other hand, a candidate who has gotten 3.6's and 3.7's throughout their academic career may be a very good candidate.  That being said, a low GPA (below 3.0) is often a sign of a bad candidate.

Perhaps this is obvious, but I'll say it anyway:  the more you know about the candidate's work, the better.  Are they good writers?  Are they good teachers?  Do they know the literature of their field?  Do they make good presentations?  These are all very good indicators of the quality of a PhD candidate.  Note that I'm talking about knowledge of the literature, not just the ability to parrot back a few memorized facts.

\begin{blockquote}

The candidate must have been a good undergraduate (3.8+ GPA, publications, research, awards, etc.)
\end{blockquote}

There are two problems with this criterion: 1) it is not easily quantifiable and 2) it is subjective.  A good undergraduate may not be a good PhD candidate.  It is also up to your advisor to decide what is and is not a good publication, research, or award.  As someone who has been involved in hiring PhD candidates, I can tell you that I have been disappointed by candidates who thought they were fantastic, only to find out that they weren't.

\begin{blockquote}

The candidate must have been a good graduate student (good grades, etc.)
\end{blockquote}

This is basically the same problem as the first criteria.  It's not quantifiable.  And it's subjective.  In my experience, good grades are usually a good indicator, but they're not always a perfect indicator.

\begin{blockquote}

The candidate must have good recommendations (strongly recommend for admission, etc.)
\end{blockquote}

This is a good indicator, but it's not perfect.  There's nothing to stop a student from asking for recommendations from professors who are friends or colleagues.  If the student does this, the recommendations may not be very helpful.

Comment: This is a good answer.  I would add that the candidate should also have a clear sense of what they want to do after they finish the Ph.D.  A Ph.D. prepares students for a career in academia, but there are many other options, such as industry, government, or non-profit.  It's a good idea to know what you want to do with your Ph.D., and to have a plan to get there.

