\section{You can fire the employee for the act of recording you, but it will be difficult to prove}

Generally, two-party consent states require the consent of both parties before a conversation can be recorded.  Most often, this takes the form of an explicit statement by one party asking the other to record the conversation.  But states will also allow the use of "implied consent," where the circumstances make it obvious to everyone that the conversation is being recorded.  This is typically limited to situations where the conversation is taking place in a public place where it's normal to be recorded (such as a store or a restaurant).  But there are also cases where a court will allow "constructive consent" where the circumstances are such that it was obvious to the other party that the conversation was about to be recorded.  This can happen in a hotel room, for instance, where a hidden camera is visible to the other party.

In this situation, it's not clear that the employee had the intent to record the conversation, and it's certainly not clear that the employee knew that he was recording you, which is required for "constructive consent."  So unless you somehow manage to get the employee to confess, you could find yourself in a difficult legal position.

You could also be in a difficult legal position if you fired the employee for something that he wasn't actually doing.  You can't fire someone for something he didn't do, and it's unlikely that you'd have any other evidence that the employee was even recording.  You could claim that he was constructively recorded, but if you can't prove that, then you've created a situation where you're basing your decision on the word of one employee against the word of another.  That's an extremely difficult situation to be in, and in a lot of states, you could end up being sued for defamation or wrongful termination.

\section{You \em{might} be able to fire the employee for another reason}

There are some states that allow a one-party consent recording to be used.  In a one-party consent state, you can record a conversation without the other person's express permission, but you \em{must} inform the other party that you're recording the conversation.

It's not clear that this would apply to your situation.  You say that the employee recorded you in a "restaurant after closing with the doors locked," which implies that the employee was the only person in the restaurant.  In that case, he would have had to tell you that the conversation was being recorded, which he didn't do.

On the other hand, it's possible that you were in the restaurant with the employee, and you just didn't realize that he was recording you.  In that case, it's possible that he did inform you, and just didn't inform you that the conversation was being recorded.  (It's also possible that he didn't inform you at all, but that would fall under the one-party consent rules for a "public place" recording.)

\section{You should talk to an employment law attorney}

Ultimately, the best thing you can do is talk to an employment law attorney.  They will be able to tell you exactly what the law is in your state, and if you have a good case, they can even represent you in a lawsuit.

